snippet.textDisplay: You’re right, Rian Johnson isn’t a hack, a fantastic writer and a fantastic director and he was just given the wrong Star Wars movie and while I really like The Last Jedi.. and kinda The Rise of Skywalker and Force Awakens.. Disney kinda botched this trilogy. They definitely should have had one person directing or writing these movies instead of trying a weird relay race which is neat in concept but not for Star Wars. While I personally liked this trilogy, mostly because I like the story the told with Ben, I really hope they learn from the criticisms and problems people have. I hope they give a trilogy or series to someone who can give a consistent and cohesive story and theme and has a small amount of fan service and references but mostly doesn’t hinge the original trilogy and that particular nostalgia so much. There’s enough here that I like that I can’t really hate it but I don’t think I love but I know there are better stories that can be told and Disney is capable of getting the people to do it, just look at The Mandalorian and I’m sure the criticisms coming from here mixed with the praise for The Mandalorian things will get a bit better and maybe they’ll even learn to slow down the release of movies but I doubt that.

snippet.textDisplay: To be honest, yeah it's a terrible film, but you can tell that J.J. wanted something better for this trilogy and would've fleshed out all of the plot holes if he had the time in one film. Abrams tried his best to make the fans happy and give us something that we would enjoy. And he did the best he could considering what he was given. So I applaud J.J. for not giving us a completely uneventful and shitty end to the saga. I just wish he could've been able to make TLJ so we could've had a good trilogy.

You know what might have been a better story for this trilogy?
Have episode VII be about Luke’s school, at which both Rey and Kylo are students; the culmination of the movie is Kylo destroying the school and becoming a Darth Vader like figure. That’s just my opinion on what could have been a more interesting story 🤷‍♀️

snippet.textDisplay:
Just two points - one, where does this love for Johnson's Looper come from? Me and a few friends saw it in the cinema - all film students, so I like to think we're not idiots - and we all found it to be pretty dull, boring and a bit shit.

That said, Last Jedi I think was an example of a director trying to subvert and meta textually analyse a famous property, but it's probably not the property to do it with, and, as you said, it works best as a stand-alone spin-off rather than the second part of a trilogy.

As it stands, the trilogy kinda goes:

Force Awakens - Fuck yeah, nostalgia!
Last Jedi - Nostalgia is bad. Move on from the past.
Rise of Skywalker - YEAH NOSTALGIAS BACK GUYS.

Last Jedi would be a fine film if it wasn't a Star Wars film, and hadn't left Abrams with nowhere to go for the third.

Johnson fucked this trilogy up by trying to be David Lynch in the middle-arc of a narrative.

snippet.textDisplay:
Honestly, for all the controversy this movie, and the disney trilogy in general brought, I got to give them major props on one front.


So often a revival of an old series comes out and they either reboot the original story, or add new enemies and plot. Or even worse, degrassi the next generation it. Disney managed to pull off an incredible feat. One that few manage to truly get as right as they did. The ending of The Rise of Skywalker seems to put a full stop on the ongoing events. Even though it was a "new war" the ending feels even more of a definitive ending than the original definitive ending, managing to dwarf it. I won't say the end of 6 felt incomplete, but, after seeing the end of 9, the end of 6 seems like it wasn't quite a complete ending.


Adding on to an existing story without adding a whole new story line that's loosely tied to the original is something so few and far between that I can't even think of a another series that managed to get it so right. I don't know what Disney's plan is here. I have doubts they will end it here, or with one more anthology as they should. However, I think it's important to recognize the writer's ability to add on non-destructively to a story that was already finished.


Edit: Posted my opinions before watching his video, and, I stand by my opinions. I was looking at what it was he didn't like, and I think part of my enjoyment is my lack of serious attachment to the series. I never noticed chewbaca was the only one to not get a medal. I miss a lot of the smaller nods others don't miss. I guess part of the reason I can enjoy the story so much is I'm not constantly being unimmersed by nods to the original movies and other 4th wall breaks. Don't get me wrong, I've seen all the movies. However, there's no childhood attachment. I saw the prequels growing up as a kid. My only real "childhood" memory of star wars was being in 3rd grade with revenge of the sith came out as me and my friends relished the absolute badassary of vader, who was coming into his own in that movie. General Greavis too... As a child I enjoyed them as much as any other action movie. Looking back, it's nothing special. I ended up re-watching everything when I watched through the whole series and you can see the mistakes, however, I wouldn't skip on them. I'm a fan of watching the series as 4, 5, 1, 2, 3, then 6. For anyone who hasn't seen it, I think you can get the most enjoyment out of this, with the addition of rogue 1 before 4 and after 6, moving on to 7, 8, solo, and 9. I think a lot of people who enjoy the series seriously will absolutely hate me for my choice of order, but I think it allows you to get the full affect of the events unfolding as one big fluent narrative. That big fluent narrative (rather than just 1 trilogy viewpoint) is what allowed me to really enjoy this movie, and all the others. I was never caught up in the behind the scenes crap. I had no idea how fragmented the story was (though I can admit it seems a bit confusing for a while). However, I was able to suspend that thought and in the end, I personally enjoyed finale we were given, including the ridiculously large amount of ships. Perhaps it was overdone for a star wars movie, but, I think it help cement this as a true finale. Until disney makes another movie anyway. Personally, I don't think they'd ever be able to add more to these events (excluding maybe some kind of anthology in the middle) and not have to create an entire new enemy with new stakes and new weapons.
